pros:
Before I joined the “real” SAP, I’ve doing & using SAP R3/4 for 15+ years, however only now I know more about SAP, the culture, wow, and a lot more. 
1. Buddy program- you always have some colleague assigned to help you and support you wherever and whenever; 
2. You clearly feel you are welcomed and loved by your team ;
3. Your work life balance is one of the KPI of your boss;
4. Ask questions, don’t be afraid and you always get answers;
5. Numerous tools and methodology far far beyond imagination, like jumping into ocean of knowledge;
6. You are always spoiled by HR with so many activities, parties, warm emails, ballots;
7. Maternity and parental leave for sure;
8. You get birthday greetings from global CEO!
9. A true diversity environment,  just be yourself;
10. Same in any SAP offices I’ve been traveled to.

- Excellent and young work atmosphere;
- Lots of learning resources available along with opportunities to value yourself through personal training or certifications;
- Possibility of working abroad, in great client companies (if you're lucky!);
- Good work/life balance;
- It's an excellent company for recent graduates;

cons:
- Hard career progression;
- Low salaries;
- In practice there is no consultants career plan;
- Many consultants stay long periods without projects and then when you get one, it often can be neither interesting nor challenging;
- 3 years permanency clause;

pros:
1. Dominant position in enterprise software (esp. ERP) market;
2. New innovations such as in-memory computing (HANA), mobility and cloud;
3. Employee friendly environment and reasonable work-life balance;
4. Lots of international exposures internally

cons:
a. Lots of politics, bureaucratic, and communication barriers across teams (as expected for any large organization);
b. Traditional on-premise enterprise software market is coming to a growth bottleneck;
c. In-memory computing could be a risky bet;
d. For cloud and mobility, not yet established as a dominant leader position (and sometimes a follower);
e. Pressures are concentrated on revenue generating and enablement teams (sales, presales, etc), while some other teams are quite lay back and enjoying life;
f. Relatively high turnover at all levels, esp. the executive changes bring lots of confusion and discontinuities.

- back to ABAP;
- very slow, monstrous decision making process;
- lots of people working nowhere but at SAP;

pros:
* collaborative environment. This is key to feeling welcome and at ease at work. And my cross-team colleagues helped me feel like one of their own from my on-boarding 7 months ago;
* mature (balanced, no drama) work approach;
* good compensation in accordance to the knowledge and potential level;
* excellent work-life balance;
* professional and friendly recruitment experience: moved very fast for such a company of this size, to the point, friendly, answered all questions asked, multiple assessment levels (future peers included);
* excellent ergonomics at the office (e.g. adjustable chairs and desks, natural light for all employees);
* great benefits both at the office and outside of it, all to support balanced and healthy (both physically and mentally) and smart individuals;
* work ethic: delivering quality to make the world run better. And this is for real, not just a bunch of words. (I am really proud to work in such a company);
* inclusive: diversity is taken into consideration in all its dimensions;
* flexible working hours, as long as the deliverables and timelines are met;
* no micromanagement, but empowering approach;
* I feel I can learn from my peers and management team. The country manager is someone I came to admire, being around the man on a daily basis;
* talent is valued here, and you are really supported into becoming your best, if this is what drives you as well.
